teams that have, you know, came up at the beginning

00:16:31.410 --> 00:16:32.910
of last year within the ecosystem.

00:16:32.970 --> 00:16:34.740
There's going to be some sort of new theory, I

00:16:34.740 --> 00:16:36.280
'm sure, that's going to emerge.

00:16:36.590 --> 00:16:40.250
Otherwise, you know, I think the biggest boon is

00:16:40.270 --> 00:16:43.670
going to be some VCs taking a contrarian bet

00:16:43.670 --> 00:16:44.100
.

00:16:44.110 --> 00:16:48.600
The first word in the acronym VC is venture, right?

00:16:48.750 --> 00:16:52.040
There is some sort of risk involved with these things, and

00:16:52.050 --> 00:16:55.450
someone will eventually have to take a chance on this space if

00:16:55.490 --> 00:16:58.780
they want to see a return on that investment, right?

00:16:58.820 --> 00:17:01.180
So, I think it's going to be both.

00:17:02.020 --> 00:17:04.420
VCs need to get off the sidelines and understand what

00:17:04.420 --> 00:17:07.140
the theory of the case here and what the opportunity is,

00:17:07.140 --> 00:17:10.420
and then other people are going to have to shift strategies.

00:17:10.420 --> 00:17:15.960
I wanted to ask you, talk about AI-generated

00:17:16.090 --> 00:17:21.210
slop, and I wanted to ask how you contrast that to

00:17:21.210 --> 00:17:25.290
the way that Graves uses LLMs to help folks

00:17:25.580 --> 00:17:30.250
generate feeds, and how you sort of make that distinction when

00:17:30.250 --> 00:17:32.200
you think, like, an LLM is being used

00:17:32.540 --> 00:17:34.500
effectively or not effectively.

00:17:34.650 --> 00:17:35.560
Sure.

00:17:35.560 --> 00:17:39.340
LLMs should be fundamentally in service of a curator,

00:17:39.340 --> 00:17:40.060
right?

00:17:40.090 --> 00:17:41.650
They should not replace a curator.

00:17:41.690 --> 00:17:44.630
These should not be systems that are, you know, simple

00:17:44.630 --> 00:17:47.050
drop-in, just make this thing work for me sort

00:17:47.110 --> 00:17:48.220
of experiences.

00:17:48.470 --> 00:17:51.100
That is not a durable way to build software with LL

00:17:51.100 --> 00:17:54.000
Ms, because, again, this is a dynamic adversarial

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:57.380
environment where systems will adapt accordingly, right?

00:17:57.450 --> 00:18:00.970
Our theory is that, you know, what we built a

00:18:01.030 --> 00:18:05.470
year ago was an AI-generation tool where you can explain

00:18:05.470 --> 00:18:08.400
, I want this feed into the system, and then it

00:18:08.400 --> 00:18:11.100
will design a sort of initial spec of, like, this

00:18:11.100 --> 00:18:14.040
is where you should take it, and one of the other

00:18:14.310 --> 00:18:17.890
benefits of it ultimately being a JSON spec, right, is

00:18:17.890 --> 00:18:21.400
that it is an interpretable document, right?

00:18:21.400 --> 00:18:23.800
You can share this document and say, this is how,

00:18:23.800 --> 00:18:25.900
this is the logic of this space, right?

00:18:25.950 --> 00:18:28.770
That opens itself up to other adversarial things, but it

00:18:28.770 --> 00:18:31.310
's also a, you know, function of transparency, so

00:18:31.350 --> 00:18:31.500
.

00:18:32.060 --> 00:18:32.890
It's a view source.

00:18:32.910 --> 00:18:33.380
Yeah.

00:18:33.700 --> 00:18:36.450
Another question.

00:18:36.570 --> 00:18:40.720
Devin, again, thank you very much for being a

00:18:40.780 --> 00:18:43.820
returning sponsor, round two.

00:18:43.930 --> 00:18:44.950
Thank you very much.

00:18:44.970 --> 00:18:46.760
You've done so much.

00:18:46.760 --> 00:18:48.540
We appreciate you.
